         <h1>Tommy Flowers, 92, Dies; Broke Nazi Codes </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Tommy Flowers , a British civil servant with a genius for electronics whose pioneering Colossus computers enabled the Allies to decode top-level German military communications in World War II , died on Oct. 28 at his home in London . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 92 . <br><blue>3</blue>The Colossus machines were once described by Mr. Flowers as a '' string-and-sealing-wax affair . '' <br><blue>4</blue>But they became the capstone of the intelligence operation known as Ultra , which outwitted the Germans and , in the words of Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower , '' saved thousands of British and American lives . '' <br><blue>5</blue>Soon after Britain went to war with Germany in the summer of 1939 , many of its leading mathematicians , cryptographers and technicians were assembled at Bletchley Park , a Victorian-era estate 55 miles north of London . <br><blue>6</blue>It was there that the German military codes were broken . <br><blue>7</blue>Mr. Flowers was named a Member of the British Empire , receiving a $ :1,000 award for the decoding of military messages from the German Enigma machines in the war 's early years . <br><blue>8</blue>But his major contribution came in 1944 and 1945 , when the computers he designed tackled the codes produced by the more sophisticated German Lorenz machines . <br><blue>9</blue>The deciphering of those messages , between Hitler 's headquarters and his generals , gave the British and Americans insight into German defenses for the D-Day invasion and subsequent battles . <br><blue>10</blue>Thomas Harold Flowers was born on Dec. 22 , 1905 , in London , where his father installed bakery machines . <br><blue>11</blue>Early on , he showed a penchant for engineering . <br><blue>12</blue>As his son Kenneth related , '' When he was age 5 he was told he 'd just gotten a baby sister . <br><blue>13</blue>He said , ' I 'd rather have a No. 5 Meccano , ' '' a construction kit . <br><blue>14</blue>Mr. Flowers obtained a degree in engineering from the University of London and in the late 1930 's experimented with electronic telephone transmissions for the research arm of the British Post Office , which oversaw the nation 's communications . <br><blue>15</blue>He was enlisted in the Bletchley Park effort in 1942 , although he later developed his computer at the Post Office 's Dollis Hill research station in London . <br><blue>16</blue>The British deduced the principals behind the Lorenz codes , but had been frustrated in developing technology for quick decoding . <br><blue>17</blue>The machine the British were using in 1943 was slow and unreliable , and sometimes caught fire . <br><blue>18</blue>Over a period of nine months , working with several senior engineering aides and a few dozen technicians , Mr. Flowers developed the first large electronic-valve computer , overcoming the skepticism of Bletchley Park officials . <br><blue>19</blue>Colossus measured 16 feet by 7 feet , weighed one ton and was put together partly with standard telephone-exchange parts , the '' string and sealing wax . '' <br><blue>20</blue>Although primitive by today 's standards , it quickly pinpointed the wheel settings used by the Germans ' Lorenz machine operators for coded messages , an essential first step in deciphering . <br><hr><br><blue>1(1)</blue>: <m_str>quick decoding</m_str> (16_19) 	<br><blue>2(2)</blue>: <m_str>the Post Office 's</m_str> (15_19) 	<m_str>the British Post Office , which oversaw the nation 's communications</m_str> (14_29) 	<br><blue>3(2)</blue>: <m_str>its</m_str> (5_17) 	<m_str>Britain</m_str> (5_3) 	<br><blue>4(2)</blue>: <m_str>military messages</m_str> (7_21) 	<m_str>those messages</m_str> (9_4) 	<br><blue>5(22)</blue>: <m_str>He</m_str> (15_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Flowers</m_str> (18_20) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (8_2) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (15_13) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (12_2) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (15_16) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (12_9) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (8_14) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (12_13) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (12_16) 	<m_str>He</m_st